{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_douglasfir_ver01/data/sn86075189/00414211045/1957081601/0402.xml":{"full_text":"Smeltermen's Celebration Draws!\nThousands In \"Smelter City\"\nANACONDA\u2014Thousands of Ana\ncondans and people from nearby\nareas attended the annual Smelter\nmen's celebration at Washoe Park\nlast Thursday.\nThis annual event is sponsored by\nLocal 117 of International Union of\nMine, Mill Smelter Workers, and\nis a principal entertainment highlight\nof each year in the Smelter City.\nOpening the festival was the chil\ndren's parade through the business\ndistrict starting at 10 o'clock. Awards\nwere presented winners in the float\ndivisions at the city common after\nthe procession. Each child participat\ning received a dollar and a balloon.\nThe program then proceeded to\nWashoe Park. A treat was distributed\nto the children at 1 o'clock. There\nwere refreshments, ham sandwiches,\npotato salad, ice cream and coffee\nfor smeltermen and their families. A\nprogram of races followed.\nThe speaking program featured Or\nville Larson, vice president of the\nInternational Union of Mine, Mill\nSmelter Workers; and Forrest An\nderson, Attorney General of Mon\ntana,\nAwards were presented after which\nthe annual baseball game was played.\nAnodes met the South Side Parks\nat 6 o'clock.\nConcluding the entertainment were\ntwo dances. Young people were guests\nat the Daly gym. Others danced at the\nAnaconda Company Employes Club.\nThe club chorus sang. Music for the\ndances was by two four-piece orches\ntras, provided by local union of Mu\nsicians, through the assistance of that\nunion's performance trust fund of\nthe recording industry.\nMore than 3,000 silver dollars and\nballoons were given away at the pa\nrade, $5,000 worth of treats and 9,000\nsandwiches. Entertainment was by the\nNygaard band including Delores Bol\nkovatz, James Murray, Cathy Mayra,\nPauline Frazer, Emil Peterson, Judy\nTomlinson, Michele Joy and Harold\nNygaard.\nGeneral Chairman Ed Johnson in\nUnemployment In Montana Up\nThree Times Over Since 1952\nBy VIC REINEMER, Exec. Secy, to\nSen. James E. Murray\nThe fever's on in the Capitol. You\ncan tell it by the way Majority Leader\nLyndon Johnson thumbs his shirt and\neyes colleagues who stray from dis\ncussion of the pending business. You\ncan tell it from the way legislators\nand lobbyists work feverishly for the\nrule, report, conference or whatever\nit is that is holding up legislation\nthey want. You can tell it from the\nshortened tempers and bleary eyes.\nSenator Kerr Wants to Know\nIs Ike Planning a Recession?\nFrom The MACHINIST\nU. S. Sen, Robert Kerr of Okla\nhoma has challenged President Eisen\nhower to tell the American people \"in\nsimple honesty\nagreed to permit a recession. The\nOklahoma senator posed the question\nfollowing repeated newspaper reports\nthat Administration economic plan\nners believe a \"moderate recession\"\nis the only way to cope with the\n\"problems of prosperity.\nAccording to the published stories,\nAdministration planners want a little\nunemployment and suffering to take\nwhether he has\n\nthe peak off inflation and \"push the\nunions back into line.\"\nKerr and other members of the\nSenate Finance Committee have\nrepeatedly questioned Administra\ntion witnesses about this recession\nplanning during the current com\nmittee investigation of the finan\ncial condition of the United States.\nUsually, the witnesses have replied\nby avoiding the word recession. In\nstead, they use expressions like \"level\ning down'' or \"rolling readjustment.\n\"Apparently,\" Senator Kerr told\none of the witnesses last week, \"you\nthink a little recession by another\nname smells a lot sweeter.\"\nKerr's comment brought laughter\nto the committee room;\nBut the Oklahoma senator, by sharp\nquestioning of Administration spokes\nmen, is making it clear that the na\ntion's workers and businessmen are\n\ntroduced Ed Fahey, business agent,\nas program chairman. Larry Riley,\npresident of the local, Ernie Salvas,\ndistrict board member, Barney Rask\nof the Butte Miners Union; Orville\nLarson, vice president; Attorney Gen\neral Forrest Anderson, and Bob Em\nmons spoke.\nLarson brought greetings from the\ninternational union and congratulated\nthe smeltermen on their holiday. He\nspoke on the decreased prices of\nmetals in the mining industry and the\npromotion of a tariff on zinc and\nlead on imports into this country.\nAnderson reviewed labor history\nin the state and nation and also con\ngratulated the smeltermen on their\nday. He urged co-operation among\nunion members.\nMusical organizations participating\nin the parade were the Anaconda high\nschool band and Elks drum and bugle\ncorps.\nAs in past years, Anaconda stores\nand business offices were closed in\nobservance of Local 117's anniversary\ncelebration.\nCommittee co-chairmen and mem\nbers of the commitees in charge of\nthe festival were Alex Mattson, Steve\nWimsett, William Villenauve, Larry\nRiley, John Lyons, Jim Clarke, Gene\nCorcoran, John Schovolt, Jack Mc\nAndrews, Robert Moore, Tom Dick\nson, Ed Fahey, Pat Mulcahy, Therold\nHowe, Arthur Ivie, Sam Snyder, A1\nLake, Einar Ekstrom, Charles Swi\nhart, Edwin Davis, Everett Tyrrel,\nFrank Vanderhule, Tom Deehan, Pat\nrick Meehan, Bill Melogue, John\nDoyle, Hans Bakke, Virgil Gochanour,\nEdward Martin, Vance Marvin, Har\nold Swanson, Leo Staat, Larry Mou\nsing, Louis Huseby, Gunnar Thol\nstrom, Ray Smith, Aaron Johnson,\nLyman Thayer, Frank Reiss, Ernest\nFredregill, John Barkley, John Enhi,\nMack Allen, Frank Bonner, Walter\nPietron, John Janosko, Walter Men\nsing, Richard Johnson, Dan Vaughn,\nDon Blodgett, W. C. Kessler, Kenneth\nBarker.\nThere are still a couple weeks of\nheavy work ahead (most of the dates\nin the office pools on adjournment\ndate hover between August 24 and\nAugust 29) but with the civil rights\nfilibuster averted most members are\nanxious to wind it up and make at\nleast some of their August commit\nments elsewhere. One representative,\nnot from Montana, said Wednesday\nas he gathered his bags that he didn't\nknow what Congress was going to do\nbut he had just adjourned. And away\nnot amused by recession planning, no\nmatter what the Administration calls\nit.\nAmong the first to call attention\nto the recession planning were the\nJournal of Commerce, a business and\nfinancial newspaper published at New\nYork, and David Lawrence, syndi\ncated Washington columnist and edi\ntor of U. S. NEWS AND WORLD\nREPORT.\nSaid the Journal;\n\"The evidence now points strong\nly to the conclusion that both the\nAdministration and\nserve authorities believe that a\n'moderate recession now' would be\na small price to pay for the avoid\nance of another boom-and-bust\nlater on.\"\nsion. That means some unemploy\nment.\nThe big question is, continued the\nJournal, \"whether the Administra\ntion should take the public into its\nconfidence by trying to explain its\ngoals and methods\nLawrence put it this way;\n\"It's plainly evident that the Ad\nministration has concluded that it\ncan expect no help from either big\nbusiness or big unions in restricting\nthe wage-price spiral. Only one thing\nis going to stop the inflation and\nstabilize the purchasing power of the\ndollar for a while and that's a reces\n(Continued on Page Two)\nOF MONT\u00c0TJ A\nHELENA\nfeX ,A v\nn\nv,\nNi\nf\ny\nX\nv\nT\na\n\u2022\"I\nini ii\n\n/n7\nn\nI\n//z\n'nr\nii r r r I\nMONTANA'S ONLY STATEWIDE INDEPENDENT NEWSPAPER\nVol. XVIII\u2014No. 36\nHELENA, MONTANA, AUGUST 16, 1957\n$3.00 Per Year\n195';/ Acreage Reserve Sets Up\nSo'f lank Base,\nW I nIGTON, D. C.\u2014(NFU)\u2014The 1958 Acreage Re-^\nserve Y ram, which includes new 7 regulations and restric\njnnounced last week as soon as the 1958 agricultural\ntions,\nappropriations bill had cleared Congress. Since the changes\nmay have far-reaching effects upon the planting decisions of\nwinter wheat growers, there is not much time before winter\nVv w.\nwheat planting time for farmers\nbecome familiar with the new regu\nlations.\nThe most important changes in the\nAcreage Reserve program are\n1. Establishment of a total crop\nacreage figure for each farm, to be\nbased primarily on past production\nhistory and known as the \"Soil\nBank base,' 7 with the requirement\nthat total harvested acreage in 1958\nbe held below the \"base'' by the\nequivalent of the number of acres\nplaced in the Soil Bank.\n(This Soil Bank base provision has\nbeen in effect for the Conservation\nReserve since the beginning of that\nprogram. For 1958, it will apply to\nfarms taking part in either or both\nof the Soil Bank programs.)\n2. A limit of $3,000 on the total\nof 1958 Acreage Reserve payments\nwhich can be made to any one pro\nducer, as required by legislative\naction.\nSOIL BANK BASE\nCrops making up the Soil Bank\nbase will, in general, be all crops pro\nduced for harvest on a farm, except\nhay crops. In addition to the six basic\nhe went to the north country, on the\nAugust vacation he'd promised the\nwife and kids.\nUNEMPLOYMENT INCREASING\nThursday Senators Murray and\nMansfield documented on the Sen\nate floor the number of shut-downs\nand lay-offs in Montana recently.\nHere are the grim statistics.\nUnemployment three times as great\nas it was five years ago,\nButte-Anaconda\u20142,000 miners laid\noff in past 90 days.\nBillings\u2014Unemployment up .275\nper cent since a year ago.\nRoundup\u201452 miners, 5 railroaders\nlaid off.\nSuperior\u201440 lumber mill workers\nlaid off, meaning a short season for\n60 men in the woods.\nMissoula\u201467 Bonner mill men, and\n10 men in the woods crew affected.\nTungsten mine closed.\n60 men laid off\nDillon\nColumbia Falls\nby Anaconda Aluminum Co.\nFarmers and ranchers\u2014Having to\nsell seven more calves, at today's\nprices, to buy the combine which sold\nfor $200 less in 1952 when beef on\nthe hoof brought $8.50 per hundred\nweight more than it does today.\n\"These are the facts,\" summarized\nMurray. \"They show why I and Sena\ntor Mansfield, Representative Metcalf\nand Representative Anderson are so\nanxious to get construction of Yel\nlowtail Dam under way, so that the\nidle construction workers in the Bil\nlings area can get to work on this\nproject which will mean so much to\nthe long-range economy and indus\ntrial development of my state.\n\"They show why we have been try\ning to get the Atomic Energy Com\nmission and its subcontractors to\nutilize coal from the Roundup field,\nas it did in the past,\n\"They show why we pressed the\nFederal Housing Administrator and\nthe President to put into effect the\nliberalized FHA loan program en\nacted by Congress, so that lumber\ncould go into sorely needed houses.\n\"They show why we fought for a\ntungsten program,\n\"They show why we are asking for\n(Continued On Page Four)\nto#\ncrops, crops such as feed grains, an\nnual grasses cut for seed, oilseeds,\ncowpeas, potatoes, Commercial vege\ntables, field and canning peas and\nbeans; will be included.\nThe Soil Bank blase for individual\nfarms will be established by county\nASC committees primarily on the\nbasis of the average of land devoted\nto Soil Bank base crops during the\npast two years\u20141956 and 1957.\nWhere a farm already has a base es\ntablished under the Conservation Re\nserve program, that base will apply.\nIn the Acreage Reserve agreement,\nparticipating farmers will agree to\nlimit their harvest of Soil Bank base\ncrops. The limit, called the \"permitted\nacreage,\" will be determined by sub\ntracting the number of acres in the\nAcreage Reserve from the total in\nthe Soil Bank base. (Provisions of the\nConservation Reserve program also\ncall for reductions below the Soil\nBank base. If both programs are in\neffect on a farm, the required reduc\ntion in harvested acres below the base\nwill be the total acres in the AR and\nCR for that year.)\nHarvesting more total acreage from\na farm than the \"permitted acreage\nwill make the producer subject to a\ncivil penalty, in addition to the loss\nof Acreage Reserve payment. The\ncivil penalty is 50 per cent of the\npayment which would have been made\nfor compliance with all provisions of\nthe program. (This is the same civil\npenalty which applies if the producer\npermits grazing of the Acreage Re\nserve, takes a crop from it that year,\nor harvests more acres of the signed\nAnother Small Bank\nIncreases Capital\nAnother small Montana bank, the\nBasin State Bank of Stanford, has\nannounced an increase in its capital\nand surplus accounts.\nAccording to the JUDITH BASIN\nPRESS, the Stanford bank began its\n47th year of operation August 2 by\nincreasing its capital from $50,000\nto $75,000 and its surplus from $25,\n000 to $75,000, for a new capital\naccount of $150,000.\nLegislation encouraging banks to\nincrease their capital account was\nenacted by the 1957 Legislature when\nthe tax classification on that type of\nbank moneys was cut by over 400 per\ncent\u2014from 30 to seven per cent.\nAlthough much was said by bank\nlobbyists on how bankers would hasten\nto increase their capital accounts\nshould enabling legislation (SB 15)\nbe put on the books, to date only a\nhandful of smaller banks have in\ncreased their capital accounts. Every\nsign continues to point to SB 15 be\ning little more than a means whereby\nthe banking business engineered for\nitself a very substantial cut in taxes\npaid to the various counties at a time\nwhen all other segments of the Mon\ntana economy are finding their tax\nbills greatly increased because of leg\nislative action.\u2014HLB.\nThe Teachers' Voice\ntt\n\nIn making up the two vacation issues which were presented by a\ngroup of teachers at Montana State University, space precluded\npublication of two very good articles. Accordingly, this week we\ncomplete the TEACHERS' VOICE for 1957 by presenting else\nwhere in this issue \"Economy In Education\" and an analysis of\npaying teachers on a merit rating basis. We are sure you will enjoy\nthese two articles, just as a number of you report having enjoyed\nthe two vacation issues put out by the teachers.\nup crop than the difference between\nthe farm allotment and the Acreage\nReserve.)\nPAYMENT LIMITATION\nIn accordance with legislative pro\nvision, not more than a total of $3,000\nin Acreage Reserve payments for\n1958 can be made to any one produc\ner. If aci'eage of two or more eligible\nbasic commodities is put into the\nAcreage Reserve, the $3,000 limit\napplies to the total of all AR pay\nments. (This limit does not include\npayments under the Conservation Re\nserve program. There is a separate\nlimit of $5,000 in the total of Con\nservation Reserve annual payments\nwhich can be made in any one year.\nIf a producer put acreage in both\nthe AR and CR, he could be eligible\nfor payments up to $3,000 and $5,000\nrespectively\u2014or a total of $8,000 for\nthe year.)\nContinued on Page Four)\nStockholders Reap\nReward of Tax\nSubsidy Program\nWASHINGTON, D. C.\u2014 (CNS)\nTwelve electric utilities converted\nfast tax write-offs into $19.4 million\nworth of tax-free dividends to stock\nholders in just one year (1955), a\nSenate subcommittee has discovered.\nSenator Estes Kefauver (D-Tenn.)\nsaid Congress didn't intend any such\n\"bonanza for stockholders.\" William\nW. Gatchell, Federal Power Com\nmission's general counsel, agreed.\n\"FPC doesn't consider fast tax write\noffs as windfalls. They're meant to\ninduce private firms to undertake\nprojects that benefit national de\nfense,'' he said.\nGatchell said any extra gravy for\nstockholders was \"an unintended ben\nefit\" of the fast tax write-off pro\ngram.\nKefauver pointed out that not\none of the 12 utilities passed along\nany benefit to its customers\nthrough lower rates.\nFPC said it would begin hearings\nhere September 17 on proposed rules\nchanges to require both gas and pow\ner utilities to pass on the benefits of\ntax subsidies to their customers.\nLast month, the Treasury estimated\nthat it has already lost between $4,\n295 million and $4,912 million as a\nresult of fast tax write-offs since\n1950. If corporate income taxes drop\nnext year, as scheduled, these losses\nwill accumulate at the rate of almost\n$1,500 million a year.\nFalls Oil Workers Make\nSubstantial Improvements\nGREAT FALLS\nUnder a new\ncontract recently negotiated between\nPhillips Petroleum and the local Oil\nWorkers union, organized workers of.\nthe company a per cent\nwage increase.\nIn addition to the wage increase,\nthe new one-year contract also pro\nvides for nine paid holidays, two-and\none-half time pay for holiday work,\nthree weeks vacation after 10 years'\nservice and four weeks after 20 years,\nand double time for overtime work.","height":"20085","width":"14031"}}
